At the same time, the Labour leader’s decision to stand silent during the national anthem at Tuesday’s memorial service, which was held on the 75th anniversary of the Battle for Britain air war, has raised criticism among Conservative MPs and has been featured in several front-page articles.
Corbyn’s decision not to sing the national anthem has attracted attention
Corbyn’s spokesman said he “stands up respectfully in silence” and that he acknowledges “the bravery of the Royal Air Force in the British Air War.”
Owen Smith, a member of Corbyn’s shadow government, told BBC Two Newsnight that he would have urged the Labour leader to sing the national anthem, despite the fact that he believed the royal house should be abolished.
Almost a dozen shadow ministers have refused to join Corbyn's inner circle, citing differences in economic, defence and foreign affairs, and less than one-sixth of the parliamentary party initially supported him as leader.
BBC policy correspondent Robin Brant says the differences in policy regarding the party’s role in the European Union and the government’s aid ceiling have also “accumulated” within the Labour Party since Corbyn’s appointment.
Corbyn said at a trade union meeting that the Labour Party was proposing a change that would remove the entire roof.
Hours later, Smith, the shadow government’s secretary of labor and pensions, said the party was “very clear” that they were simply opposed to the government’s plans to lower the ceiling from <0xC2><0xA3>26,000 to <0xC2><0xA3>23,000.
Corbyn will become the fifth Labour leader David Cameron has faced in the past decade when he was the leader of the Conservative Party.
The Labour leader has promised a new approach to politics and now says that he has "crowded" ideas into questions for the prime minister, and received more than 30,000 proposals.
Corbyn, a member of the Islington North Parliament, said that the nature of the Prime Minister’s Question Time is too contradictory and that he will refrain from both clever talk and speculating, promising instead to focus on serious issues such as poverty, inequality and the challenges faced by young people.
Corbyn has said that Angela Eagle, the finance secretary of the shadow government, will be his deputy in questioning classes when Corbyn is not attending – for example, when Cameron is abroad.
Mr Corbyn has also suggested that other colleagues may be allowed to speak at some point, and he has said that he has approached the President of the House of Commons, John Bercow, on the matter.
When Cameron took the lead in 2005, he said he wanted to move away from the kind of political theater that is often associated with the Prime Minister’s questioning hours, but he was later forced to admit his failure.
Since they began broadcasting in 1990, the Prime Minister's Question Time has been an important measure of the leader's judgment, his control over the House of Commons, and his position among other MPs, even though critics have criticised the Question Hour for having become a mockery that calls for far-reaching reforms.
