The video shows how the nematodes change direction as soon as the sound pulse hits them.
Scientists have grown worms with genetically engineered nervous systems to be controlled by sound wave bursts.
The tiny nematodes change direction as soon as they are hit by a sound impulse that is too high for the human ear to hear.
The impulses work by switching on genetically engineered motion neurons with ultrasound-reactive membrane channels.
Related: Scientists Read and Write Brain Activity with Light
The researchers said that worms show the functionality of a new method called sonic genetics. In it, ultrasound can be used to activate certain brain, heart and muscle cells from outside the body.
Sreekanth Chalasani, a researcher at the Salk Institute in La Jolla, California, told The Guardian that the method could one day replace deep brain stimulation, an invasive procedure where electrical impulses are directed into people’s brains to treat Parkinson’s disease.
The nematodes do not normally react to ultrasound, but Chalasani found that when they were surrounded by a liquid with microscopic bubbles, the situation changed.
He noticed that the bubbles amplified the ultrasonic waves, which then travel inside the worms.
Reinforced ultrasonic waves affect the TRP-4 ion channels, the structures that exist in the cell membranes of some worms.
Sound waves make these ion channels open and activate the cells attached to them, reports a report published in the journal Nature Communications.
In order to manufacture ultrasonically controlled nematodes, Chalasani genetically modified the worms so that part of their motion neurons contain TRP-4 ion channels.
When Chalasani applied ultrasound to modified worms, the microbubbles amplified sound waves and transmitted them to the worms, where they switch on the modified motion neurons.
The method has some of the same features as optogenetics, a groundbreaking tool that allows scientists to turn neurons on and off using light impulses.
However, Chalasani says that the use of sonogenetics may have some advantages over optogenetics.
Unlike light, which has to be transmitted along the optical fiber to a desired location inside the brain, low-frequency ultrasonic waves can pass through the tissue unobstructed, so they can be sent to the brain from the top of the skull.
"We believe that by using gene therapy and a therapeutic virus, it may be possible to make the target human nerve cells momentarily respond to an ultrasound signal in certain neurological treatments in a clinical setting," Chalasani said.
Other applications could focus on muscle cells and insulin-producing cells, he added.
