Next year, the rise will pick up to 1.1 per cent, the central bank predicts in its new inflation forecasts published in early September.
The U.S. Fed is now trying to tighten monetary policy.
The next recession in the U.S. will begin at its fastest in less than a year, but more likely within three years after the Federal Reserve begins to raise its interest rates again after a long time.
And the downturn in the financial markets begins before the next recession.
The Fed has suggested that interest rate hikes may begin as early as this week and by the end of the year at the latest.
Thus, the next recession could hit the spotlight as quickly as possible by next autumn and the turmoil of the financial markets before that.
Or at least this is what will happen if the world’s largest economy and financial markets function as they used to do – and if they react to the Fed’s blackmail like they did in the past.
These are the conclusions of the German bank’s London market research strategists Jim Reid, Nick Burns and Seb Barker in their extensive study of long-term market and economic cycles.
The bank distributed its 60-page Long-Term Asset Return Study to its international large customers last week.
The strategists who produced the study and the report do not pretend to know exactly when the Fed will start raising interest rates or what will happen in the economy and markets afterwards.
Instead, they use cool facts and calculations from economic statistics to show how the economy and markets have behaved in the past during and after the Fed’s takeovers.
In addition to historical observations, they look at which key variables in the economy and financial markets are now in the same or different pattern as at the time of previous interest rate hikes – and what the possible consequences are.
It becomes clear that both the economy and the financial markets are now in a more shattered condition to withstand the rise in interest rates than at any time since the 1950s.
Not a year into recession.
Throughout the summer and early autumn, the leaders who decide on the Fed’s monetary policy and its current stance have hinted that the time has come to raise interest rates.
The first increase in interest rates in more than nine years can already occur this week.
The matter will be resolved in the course of Wednesday and Thursday, when the so-called Open Market Committee of the Fed Board will meet to decide on the matter at its two-day meeting.
The last time the Fed raised its so-called Fed funds interest rate was in June 2006.
At that time, a series of relatively regular but small 0.25 percentage points of interest increases, which lasted exactly two years, ended, with which the Fed raised its interest rates from 1.25% to 5.25%.
The symptoms of the financial markets began in 2007 with the difficulties of the most risky housing financing in the United States, and a year later the financial crisis tore into a global doomsday nightmare.
The Great Recession came in 2009.
Last time, the severe hardships in the financial markets and the real economy started slower than has typically happened since previous Fed interest rate hikes.
Similarly, the trials were tougher and harsher than at any time since the recession of the 1930s.
Deutsche’s strategies have screened the rises and declines of the world’s largest economies and the turnarounds of the financial markets since 1950 and in some places since the beginning of the 19th century.
They have been reporting on the Fed’s borrowings and their economic and financial impact since the 1950s.
The fastest time since the beginning of the recession is less than a year, usually less than three years and on average less than three and a half years.
The rise in the financial markets has ended within a year or two after the start of the Fed’s interest rate hikes.
Since the beginning of the 1950s, the Fed has increased and decreased its interest rate by a dozen cycles of varying lengths.
Each time has differed in some respects from the other, and the multiplier is relatively scarce in the examination, so it is hardly possible to deduce anything certain about the effects of subsequent interest rate increases.
The strategy reminds us that this time many things are different.
And not just better.
Interest rates too low for too long
The decisive causes of the financial crisis, let alone the culprits, may not be unequivocally discovered even by decades of research.
But three reasons for the crisis and its increasing destructive power are perhaps somewhat undeniable:
1) In the 21st century, the Fed, the ECB of the euro area and other major central banks in the world considered their key interest rates too low for too long.
They patched up the techno bubble tracks, while growing the next one.
2) The accumulated and already excessive amount of debt in various parts of the financial and real economy over the decades grew even larger due to the excessive monetary policy of central banks.
It was the biggest debt bubble in economic history.
3) The insanely low-cost debt financing packaged in the financial economy, in particular, almost without hindrance, inflated the largest exchange rate bubbles in the history of the financial market, from stocks to real estate, bonds and commodities.
It is unlikely that there will be much controversy that the financial markets, which have risen to heights on the basis of increasingly complex leverage, were in an unusually dangerous and volatile state when the Fed and other central banks last pushed interest rates upwards.
The financial structures geared to leverage did not last long, let alone the valuation bubbles, since interest rate increases had started and the cost of debt financing had started to rise.
The risks materialised as a financial crisis, followed by a major recession.
Bigger bubble and more debt
Deutsche’s strategists do not guess what will happen next, but give cause for reflection by mentioning, for example, the following:
1) The Fed and other major central banks have now kept their monetary policy stance even lighter for even longer than before the financial crisis.
If interest rates were too low for too long before the crisis, they have now been even lower for even longer.
2) Indebtedness has not been insanely cheap for a long time, as it was ten years ago, but now debt money is literally cheaper than it is free.
Thus, the debt burden of the financial and real economy has not eased, but now, in different parts of the economy, a heavier debt burden than before the financial crisis or ever before.
(3) More and cheaper liquidity from central banks has largely remained in the financial markets, squeezing key asset classes to their most expensive level, whether at the pre-financial crisis peak or at any time.
And not only do the strategists lax the mood with the warning signs of the financial markets, but they also point out that even the US economy has not yet recovered from the financial crisis and the worst recession in decades as it has in the past.
The euro area economy has barely recovered.
In other words, the real economy is in an unusually weak state, but correspondingly, the pressures and risks in the financial markets are incomparably greater than before the financial crisis, when the Fed next starts tightening its money traps more tightly.
Perhaps the future of Albert Edwards, the strategist of the French bank Societe Generale, is not as strange as it may seem.
For some time now, he has been training the bank’s international investor clients for the following Fed turnarounds:
First the Fed raises interest rates, then the financial bubbles burst – and soon it’s time for the Fed to extinguish the financial fires with even bigger QE money syringes.
