This week, the central bank of the United States sits around a huge mahogany table for two days in a long-awaited meeting to decide whether it is time to raise the key interest rate for the first time in almost a decade.
At the other end of the central bank’s decorative, two-storey meeting room is a mural of the United States.
The map is a reminder that central bank president Janet L. Yellen and her colleagues should put the nation’s economic interests above everything else.
Congress has placed a twofold responsibility on the central bank: to maximize employment in the United States and to keep prices stable.
However, after the Great Depression, central bank governors have accepted that there is also a third, unwritten mandate: financial stability.
It is precisely this third requirement that could be a decisive factor in the decision to be announced on Thursday, which is so strict that it cannot even be predicted, a decision as to whether the US economy is ready to be weaned from the record-breaking stimulus brought about by the near-zero rate of short-term interest rates since the end of 2008.
While most of the data shows the economy is growing steadily, the recent turmoil in the global financial markets may have made pre-warned central bank officials even more frightened when it comes to increasing instability. There are fears about the impact if the federal funds rate reference value were raised by at least a quarter of a percentage point.
"Understandably, the labour market and inflation are the first and most important issues to be monitored," says Lindsey M. Piegza, Chief Financial Officer at Stifel Nicolaus & Co.
"I do believe, however, that if they are looking for justification for keeping interest rates unchanged, the increased uncertainty in the world market is a valid enough reason to wait yet," he says.
There is no consensus on the central bank's decision, which is already causing nervousness in the economy.
According to a recent Bloomberg study, about half of financial experts predict that interest rates will rise this week.
The financial markets, on the other hand, expect the central bank to delay the withdrawal, as the key indicator shows that the potential for growth is only about 30%.
This indicates a decline in the securities market if the central bank raises the level, unless the decision-makers then manage to soften the blow by promising that the next raise will not happen in the near future.
On Tuesday, the Dow Jones industrial average index rose by 228.89 points, or 1.4 percent, from a new figure of 16,599.85.
The recovery was triggered by the expectation that the central bank will maintain its level this week, says John Lonski, chief finance expert at Moody's Capital Markets Research Group.
"It's surprising if the central bank raises interest rates right now," he says.
If policymakers raise interest rates, “they will have to put a lot of effort into their policies to support the financial markets so that they don’t panic.”
Other experts argue that an elevated level would calm the financial markets because it would remove uncertainty as to when the central bank will act.
Just a month ago, it seemed that the central bank would raise interest rates by a quarter of a percentage point this month, thus taking the first small step towards a slow tightening of the monetary situation, which would confirm the stability of the US recovery.
Yellen has said in the spring and early summer that he expects the level to rise this year, despite the fact that liberals are calling for more economic development in their complaints.
While job creation slowed down in August, labour market growth has been stable this year.
The unemployment rate fell last month to 5.1 per cent, the lowest rate in seven years and close to what the Central Bank considers to be the limit for full employment.
Wage growth has shown signs of a pick-up.
While inflation is still below the central bank’s annual target of 2%, central bank decision-makers say the main reason for this is the temporary effect of significantly lower oil prices.
The economy "is able to cope with higher interest rates and also needs them, given the tightness of the labour market," says Ian Shepherdson, Chief Financial Specialist at Pantheon Macroeconomics.
However, the financial markets around the world shook last week as China devalued its currency.
The Dow Jones industrial average index fell by as much as 16 percent from its May record, as investors feared the slowdown in China’s economy would also slow global growth.
The market has recovered somewhat this month, and the Dow index is now almost 10 percent below its peak in May.
For central bank makers, market turmoil is an additional factor in a complex equation that tells when interest rates need to be raised.
“Without these financial market events and the recent news of China’s economic weakness, policymakers would tighten the bar at this meeting,” said Stephen D. Oliner, a senior researcher at the UCLA Ziman Center for Real Estate and a former central bank official.
Now he predicts that decision makers will wait at least a month to get a better idea of the effects.
"The potential impact on the U.S. economy is still unclear, and they have little information about the consequences of what happened in China," Oliner said.
The well-being of the international economy is not the central bank's main concern, so in principle it should not influence decision-making.
In practice, however, the Federal Reserve has become the world’s monetary authority.
In recent years, the central bank has exerted enormous influence.
In 2013, the insinuation of the then president, Ben S. Bernanke, that the central bank could "reduce" the increase in the amount of money, caused upheavals in the markets around the world.
In a world where markets and economies are increasingly intertwined, central bank officials are expected not only to follow developments elsewhere, but also to consult other central banks and experts in order to gain a better understanding of the global economy.
The central bank’s decision-making process is “more art than science,” says Zachary Karabell, Global Strategy Manager for asset management company Envestnet Inc.
Jeffrey Lacker, chairman of the Federal Reserve Bank in Richmond, Virginia, pointed out this month that “the central bank has previously overreacted to financial market movements that appear to be separate from economic fundamentals.”
The decision-making Federal Open Market Committee has called for the interest rate to be increased, and Mr Lacker, a member of the committee entitled to vote, refers to the 1998-99 decisions as an example.
The Asian economic crisis caused the central bank to cut its benchmark by 0.75 percentage points during three meetings "despite its limited, identifiable impact on U.S. economic growth," Lacker said.
A year later, the central bank reversed these cuts.
The central bank should only prioritise financial stability during a major crisis, as did when the market collapsed in 2008, says Adam S. Posen, a former member of the Bank of England’s interest rate fixing committee.
The latest turmoil is nowhere near its level, Posen says.
"Nobody wants a situation where raising interest rates is feared because the market will be upset," said Posen, president of the Peterson Institute for International Economics.
The Federal Reserve Act still contains a dual requirement and does not mention financial stability, and as long as that is the case, I do not think they should anticipate it.
