Weight Loss Surgery Can Help Mildly Obese Diabetics
According to a new study, the benefits of weight loss surgery for mildly obese type 2 diabetics can last at least five years.
However, it’s still too early to say whether these mildly obese diabetics will live longer after a weight loss operation than those treated in other ways than surgery.
"It takes a long time to get the mortality data," says Dr. Robin Blackstone, a specialist in weight loss surgery who wrote the editorial for a new study in the journal JAMA Surgery.
In bariatric surgery, various methods are used to reduce the size of the stomach.
They reduce hunger and limit the absorption of food.
Over the years, bariatric surgeries have been found to be effective in treating type 2 diabetes, but most of the subjects in the study have been morbidly obese, with a body mass index (BMI) of 35 or more.
The BMI, or weight-to-length ratio, is considered normal when it is between 18.5 and 24.9.
A BMI above 25 indicates that someone is overweight, and a person with a BMI above 30 is considered to be obese.
You can calculate your BMI here: 1.usa.gov/1D0ZqDv.
For this new study, researchers at the Min-Sheng General Hospital in Taiwan used data collected since 2007 to compare two types of bariatric surgery, gastric bypass surgery and gastric reduction, to drug treatments for type 2 diabetes in people who were mildly obese.
The study showed that the average BMI of those who had undergone surgery fell from 31 to 24.5 by the end of the fifth year.
At the same time, the BMI of those treated by means other than surgery remained roughly the same at 29.
Of the people who were cut, 36 percent had full and 28 percent had partial improvement in diabetes.
By comparison, in the drug-treated group, diabetes improved by only 1% and partially by about 2%.
In addition, blood pressure, triglycerides, and the "bad" LDL-cholesterol "were generally better in the surgical group," the authors noted.
The researchers also tracked patients' blood hemoglobin A1c levels, which reflect blood sugar levels over the long term.
Hemoglobin A1c levels should remain below 7%, the researchers wrote.
Post-operative haemoglobin A1c levels fell from about 9% to about 6%.
However, in the drug treatment group, it remained stable at around 8%.
However, this improved "glycemic control", as described by improved hemoglobin A1c levels, did not reduce mortality over five years, says lead researcher Dr. Chih-Cheng Hsu and colleagues.
The team also compared average results between two different types of surgery.
By the fifth year, when compared to the gastric reduction group, the gastric bypass group had lost more weight (18.7 and 14.2 kg), decreased its BMI more (7.4 and 5.1), decreased its hemoglobin A1c levels more (3.1 and 2.1 %), and was more likely to have achieved a complete remission of diabetes (16,7 %, 46, and 46).
The University of Arizona’s College of Medicine-Phoenix’s Blackstone says that while the study shows no survival or surgery after five years, there are research results from Sweden where surgery led to longer lives in heavier people.
A Swedish study found that obese people undergoing weight loss surgery were 29 percent less likely to die over a 15-year period when compared to a group that had tried more traditional treatments.
While the new study doesn’t show any improvement in survivor survival, Blackstone says the results are nevertheless encouraging for people with a BMI below 35 who are interested in surgery.
"The results of the study are crucial precisely in that they show that surgery is safe for a group with a lower body mass index," and is not associated with an increased risk of death or kidney disease, he says.
Blackstone adds that both patients and their doctors should take weight very seriously when the patient’s BMI is between 27 and 30.
"I think we'll wait too long before we take this seriously," he says.
I believe that once a person has accumulated these genetic changes that permanently prepare his body for obesity and diabetes, it is very difficult to reverse the situation.
