White House confirms Xi Jinping's visit to Washington
Chinese President Xi Jinping will make a state visit to the United States at the end of the month, a White House statement released Tuesday confirmed.
Xi’s first official visit to Washington will take place on September 25 and is a response to President Barack Obama’s visit to Beijing last November, the statement said.
The president and wife of the president, Michelle Obama, will host a dinner for Xi and his wife, Peng Liyuan, after the leaders have held bilateral talks.
“Prince X’s visit will provide an opportunity to expand US-China cooperation on a wide range of global, regional and bilateral issues of common interest, while at the same time giving President Obama and President X an opportunity to discuss constructively issues where there are disagreements,” the statement added.
During the visit, which was first announced in February, Xi is also expected to visit Seattle on his trip to Washington to meet with numerous U.S. tech leaders before continuing towards New York City and the UN General Assembly in September.
Obama and Xi are expected to discuss a number of controversial issues, including Washington’s concerns about China’s alleged cyber espionage and the country’s increased unconditionality in the controversial waters of the South China Sea.
