Xi calls for greater openness of the economy to the world
The economy needs to open up more to the outside world to promote growth, President Xi Jinping told a group tasked with steering the reform.
"China should commit itself to attracting foreign funding and expertise and to developing a policy of transparency," he said at the 16th meeting of the group leading the deepening of the general reform.
Supporting openness at the same time as pushing forward reforms will add new momentum and vitality, and create new space for economic growth, Xi said.
The Executive Board approved a series of guidelines, including a negative list restricting market access, a relaxation of border control principles, a call for state-owned companies to seize private capital, and a review of the tenant registration system.
According to the opinion, a negative list will be created, identifying the sectors and companies in which investment is not allowed.
The system is gradually being tested and improved through pilot programmes.
This change is significant, as it will give the market a greater role in allocating resources, ensure a legal business environment and make the market more transparent.
The government also loosens its control over the power it distributes to companies, thereby ensuring that companies decide for themselves how to conduct their business.
The opinion also stated that China will allow border regions to explore new models of cross-border economic cooperation and new mechanisms for developing regional growth.
More sectors will be opened up to private financiers in order to open up state-controlled sectors.
“The government will not change its policy on foreign investment and will protect the legitimate interests of foreign-funded companies and provide them with better services,” the statement said.
In addition, the application process for permanent resident permits for foreigners, the "green card", is facilitated by optimising the requirements and streamlining the application process.
The issue of guaranteeing the professional rights of lawyers and supporting professional judges and prosecutors was also discussed at the meeting.
Prime Minister Li Keqiang and senior leaders Liu Yunshan and Zhang Gaoli also attended the meeting, according to a statement published after the meeting.
